article.description: Ron Artest scored a season-high 34 points and the Kings beat the SuperSonics 105-96 for their 14th straight home win.
article.headline: Artest leads Kings to 14th consecutive win at home
article.linkText: Artest scores season-high 34; Kings win at home again
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Although road victories remain elusive, the Sacramento Kings are thriving at home. Coming off a pair of losses away from Arco Arena, Ron Artest scored a season-high 34 points and the Kings beat the Seattle SuperSonics 105-96 Tuesday night for their 14th straight home win. The Kings' home winning streak is tied for the fourth-longest in franchise history. Since Artest joined the team in late January, the Kings are 11-0 at home with him in the lineup and 16-9 overall. "It's a game we definitely had to have coming off the last two [losses]," said Brad Miller, who had 14 rebounds. "It keeps us right there with Los Angeles with our game there [Wednesday night]." With a 34-33 record, the Kings are percentage points ahead of the idle Lakers (35-34) for the seventh playoff spot in the Western Conference. After struggling offensively in the previous two games, Artest was at his best against defensively challenged Seattle, which allows the most points per game in the NBA. Working mostly inside with an effective post-up game, Artest made 10 of 18 shots, hit 11 of 15 free throws and added eight rebounds and six assists. "He was attacking the basket and he was getting to the basket on them," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "At the defensive end, he made two or three defensive plays that were really unbelievable plays." After going the first 5½ minutes without a point to open the fourth quarter and seeing its lead dwindle to one point, Artest made a jumper at the foul line to ignite an 11-4 run that put Sacramento ahead 99-91 with 3:24 left. Mike Bibby made the last of his five 3-pointers to give the Kings a 105-94 lead with 1:38 remaining. Bibby had 30 points and eight assists. Kenny Thomas had 11 points and 11 rebounds, while Bonzi Wells added 10 points for the Kings. "I thought as the game went on we wore down a little bit," said Seattle's Ray Allen, who finished with 23 points. "I don't want to blame anything, they just beat us down the stretch. In the fourth quarter is where the game is won or lost." Chris Wilcox had 16 points and 19 rebounds for the Sonics, who had won three of their previous four games. Rashard Lewis scored 15 and Robert Swift added 13 points. "Artest played a great game for them and hit the big shots when that they needed," Seattle guard Damien Wilkins said. "He defended well and was all over the court. He does what Artest does; he makes a difference." Sacramento used the inside play of Thomas and a 3-pointer at the buzzer by Artest to finish the third quarter with an 88-82 lead. The Kings trailed 60-58 at halftime. Sacramento allowed only 36 points in the second half, including 14 in the fourth quarter. "We held them down, we didn't let them get anything in the second half," said Artest, who had two blocks and helped contain Lewis to six second-half points.

Game notes
Sacramento made 19 of 20 free throws in the first half and finished 23-of-29. ... Seattle guard Earl Watson has a neck injury and did not make the trip. ... Allen and Lewis are one of only two pairs of teammates in the NBA to average 20 points or more per game. The other two are Washington's Gilbert Arenas and Antawn Jamison. ... Kings rookie Francisco Garcia played in a reserve role after missing the last nine games with an ankle sprain.
